### Test Refresh Tokens API Endpoints
### 
### This file demonstrates the difference between the two refresh token endpoints:
### 1. /auth/refresh-token - Refreshes both access and refresh tokens
### 2. /auth/refresh-access-token - Refreshes only access token, keeps same refresh token

### Variables
@baseUrl = http://localhost:3001/api/v1
@refreshToken = your-refresh-token-here

### 1. Standard Token Refresh (Both tokens renewed)
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/refresh-token
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "refreshToken": "{{refreshToken}}"
}

### Expected Response:
### {
###   "success": true,
###   "message": "Token refreshed successfully", 
###   "data": {
###     "accessToken": "new-access-token",
###     "refreshToken": "new-refresh-token"
###   }
### }

###

### 2. Access Token Only Refresh (Refresh token stays the same)
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/refresh-access-token
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "refreshToken": "{{refreshToken}}"
}

### Expected Response:
### {
###   "success": true,
###   "message": "Access token refreshed successfully",
###   "data": {
###     "accessToken": "new-access-token"
###   }
### }

###

### Use Cases:
### 
### Use /auth/refresh-token when:
### - You want maximum security (rotating refresh tokens)
### - Implementing token rotation policies
### - User hasn't been active for a while
### 
### Use /auth/refresh-access-token when:
### - You want to minimize token storage updates
### - User is actively using the application
### - You want to reduce the number of token rotations
### - Implementing a "sliding session" pattern
